[[Image:The Second Bounce of the Ball.jpg|thumb|Front cover of the first edition.]] '''''The Second Bounce of the Ball: Turning Risk into Opportunity''''' is a [[non-fiction]] book about [[entrepreneurship]], written by [[Sir Ronald Cohen]] and first published in 2007 by Weidenfeld & Nicolson, [[London]]. The book discusses what it takes to become a successful entrepreneur, and contains biographical anecdotes from the author and the company he founded, [[Apax Partners]]. The book’s title comes from Cohen’s incorrect belief that the [[Coefficient of restitution|second bounce of a ball]] is difficult to predict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ronaldcohen.net/|title=Ronald Cohen|accessdate=12 August 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914000945/http://www.ronaldcohen.net/|archivedate=14 September 2010}}</ref>
== Reviews == The book received positive reviews among the business literary critics. Robert Lenzner, editor of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, refers to Cohen as a modern-day version of [[Georges Doriot]], one of the first American [[venture capitalists]]. In his review, he highlights the biographical aspect of the book, saying that it "is at bottom about how Cohen progressed from boutique [[investment banker]] earning fees on each transaction to the risky business of financing start-up companies, and from there to the more solidly rewarding [[buyout]] or [[private equity]] business."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/opinions/2008/05/15/croesus-chronicles-doriot-oped-cz_rl_0516croesus.html?feed=rss_author|title=True Blue Gents Of Finance|last=Lenzner|first=Robert|date=May 16, 2008|work=Forbes|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref>
Jonathan Guthrie, from the [[Financial Times]], disagrees. He says that the book "is not an autobiography. But it is one of the best books written on entrepreneurship in recent years." In the review, he stated that some of the advice provided in the book can be found in other business [[self-help book]]s, but says that Sir Ronald's "analysis of entrepreneurship is broader and subtler than in most titles."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://search.ft.com/ftArticle?queryText=the+second+bounce+of+the+ball&aje=true&id=071112000052&ct=0&nclick_check=1|title=The trick is to stay ahead of the game|last=Guthrie|first=Jonathan|date=November 12, 2007 |publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=2009-01-01}}</ref>
